{"parse":{"title":"Top-left lighting","pageid":19910219,"revid":848804078,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:302px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Still_life_-_Caravaggio.png\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Still_life_-_Caravaggio.png/300px-Still_life_-_Caravaggio.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"187\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Still_life_-_Caravaggio.png/450px-Still_life_-_Caravaggio.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Still_life_-_Caravaggio.png/600px-Still_life_-_Caravaggio.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1800\" data-file-height=\"1123\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Still_life_-_Caravaggio.png\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i><a href=\"/wiki/Still_Life_with_Fruit_(Caravaggio)\" title=\"Still Life with Fruit (Caravaggio)\">Still Life with Fruit</a></i> by <a href=\"/wiki/Caravaggio\" title=\"Caravaggio\">Caravaggio</a> (1571\u20131610)</div></div></div>\n<p><b>Top-left lighting</b> is an artistic convention in which illustrations are produced so that the light appears to come from the top left of the picture.\n</p><p>Most people prefer lighting from the left when resolving a convex-concave ambiguity, and this preference may be stronger for <a href=\"/wiki/Right-handedness\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Right-handedness\">right-handed</a> people.  This is reflected in <a href=\"/wiki/Ancient_Rome\" title=\"Ancient Rome\">Roman</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Mosaic\" title=\"Mosaic\">mosaics</a> and in <a href=\"/wiki/Renaissance_painting\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Renaissance painting\">Renaissance</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Baroque_painting\" title=\"Baroque painting\">baroque</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Impressionism\" title=\"Impressionism\">impressionist</a> art.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In cartography, the predominant custom of placing the shadow on the right-hand side of <a href=\"/wiki/Cartographic_relief_depiction#Hill_profiles\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Cartographic relief depiction\">hill profiles</a> was established during the 15th century.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>  Computer interfaces tend to use top left lighting as well, although this trend has gradually shifted more towards light coming straight from the top.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (April 2010)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p><p>There are notable exceptions to this convention, such as Sandro Botticelli's <a href=\"/wiki/The_Birth_of_Venus_(Botticelli)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"The Birth of Venus (Botticelli)\">The Birth of Venus</a> due to the point of view which may represent geographical perspective and location.\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Higuey.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/0/0c/Higuey.jpg/220px-Higuey.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"164\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/0/0c/Higuey.jpg 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"305\" data-file-height=\"227\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Higuey.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Hill profiles on a 1639 map of <a href=\"/wiki/Hispaniola\" title=\"Hispaniola\">Hispaniola</a> by Joan Vinckenboons</div></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Top-left_lighting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">J. Sun and P. Perona, \"Where is the sun?\", <i>Nature Neuroscience</i>, 1(3), 183-184, 1998.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">McManus, I Christopher; Joseph Buckman; Euan Woolley (2004). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Ian_Mcmanus/publication/8003531_Is_light_in_pictures_presumed_to_come_from_the_left_side/file/79e4151052666c381c.pdf\">\"Is light in pictures presumed to come from the left side?\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span>. <i>Perception</i>. <b>33</b>: 1422. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1068/p5289\">10.1068/p5289</a><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">4 March</span> 2014</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Perception&amp;rft.atitle=Is+light+in+pictures+presumed+to+come+from+the+left+side%3F&amp;rft.volume=33&amp;rft.pages=1422&amp;rft.date=2004&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1068%2Fp5289&amp;rft.aulast=McManus&amp;rft.aufirst=I+Christopher&amp;rft.au=Joseph+Buckman&amp;rft.au=Euan+Woolley&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.researchgate.net%2Fprofile%2FIan_Mcmanus%2Fpublication%2F8003531_Is_light_in_pictures_presumed_to_come_from_the_left_side%2Ffile%2F79e4151052666c381c.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ATop-left+lighting\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">E. Imhof, <i>Cartographic Relief Presentation</i>, Walter de Gruyter, 1982, reissued by ESRI Press, 2007, <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-58948-026-1\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-1-58948-026-1\">978-1-58948-026-1</a>, pp. 2-3.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<p><br />\n</p>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Nuvola_apps_package_graphics.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/c/c3/Nuvola_apps_package_graphics.svg/30px-Nuvola_apps_package_graphics.svg.png\" width=\"30\" height=\"30\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/c/c3/Nuvola_apps_package_graphics.svg/45px-Nuvola_apps_package_graphics.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/c/c3/Nuvola_apps_package_graphics.svg/60px-Nuvola_apps_package_graphics.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"128\" data-file-height=\"128\" /></a></td><td><i>This <a href=\"/wiki/Art\" title=\"Art\">art</a>-related article is a <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Stub\" title=\"Wikipedia:Stub\">stub</a>. You can help Wikipedia by <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Top-left_lighting&amp;action=edit\">expanding it</a>.</i><div class=\"plainlinks hlist navbar mini\" style=\"position: absolute; right: 15px; display: none;\"><ul><li class=\"nv-view\"><a href=\"/wiki/Template:Art-stub\" title=\"Template:Art-stub\"><abbr title=\"View this template\">v</abbr></a></li><li class=\"nv-talk